import cv2
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
from matplotlib.pyplot import MultipleLocator

img = cv2.imread("cat.jpg")#source image
imgrgb = cv2.cvtColor(img,cv2.COLOR_BGR2RGB) #RGB image
plt.title('Task a: Original Image')

xMajorLocator=MultipleLocator(250)
yMajorLocator=MultipleLocator(200)
ax=plt.gca()
ax.xaxis.set_major_locator(xMajorLocator)
ax.yaxis.set_major_locator(yMajorLocator)

plt.imshow(imgrgb)

j(i) The channel R histogram had a little rise on the 33 bins, but the channel G histogram and channel B histogram didn't on the 33 bins. The channel G histogram and channel B histogram had a little rise on the 140 bins, but the channel R histogram didn't on the 140 bins. On the 256 bins, the channel G histogram had the most pixels, the channel R histogram had the second most pixels, the channel B histogram had the least pixels.

j(ii) No. The grayscale image kept the value of each pixel represents the intensity information of the light. The operation of isolating a color channel splitted the R channel, the G channel and the B channel from the RGB image.

j(iii) The binary theshold image only had 0 and 255 two types pixels, so the binary theshold histogram counted the pixels on the 0 bins and the pixels on the 256 bins. The grayscale image had many types pixels, so the grayscale histogram counted the pixels on the range from 0 bins to 256 bins.
